@node intro "Welcome to AutoPEG"

    @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} was developed to help those poor little graphics
    programs that don't support JPEG compression. It allows them to
    read JPEG files as 24-bit IFF files.
    
    It does not, however, allow them to write JPEG compressed files.
    Maybe later....
    
    Here's how it works: it checks @{i}every@{ui} file that is opened to
    see if it is a JPEG file. If it is not, @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} will ignore it. If
    it is, @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} will decompress it and save it as a 24-bit file. The
    program that tried to open the JPEG, will actually open the 24-bit
    file - pretty sneaky, eh?
    
    The decompressed files will go to a user-determined drawer. If you've
    got plenty of memory, you should use the RAM: disk 'cause it'll be
    much faster. If not, make sure you're disk has enough free storage.
    
    After the program is done with the file, the 24-bit file is deleted -
    which is another reason why you should use the RAM: disk. Most programs
    will open the file, quickly read the contents, then close it right away.
@endnode

@node instal "Installing AutoPEG"

    I advise you use the prepared install script that should've been
    in the archive. To use it you need the Installer program, which
    is freely available on Aminet. You probably have it already since
    tons of companies bundle it with their software.
    
    If you want to do this yourself, here's what needs to be done:
    
        1. Copy "AutoPEG" wherever you like.
        
        2. If you have a 68000, 68010, or 68020, copy AutoPEG.exe to C:
        
        3. Otherwise copy AutoPEG.exe.030 to C: as AutoPEG.exe
        
        4. Send me $50,000 US ;)

    NOTE: @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} requires AmigaDOS 2.0+

@endnode

@node use "Using AutoPEG"

    @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} takes these (optional) arguments (they can be entered from
    the command line or as tool-types, and they must be capitalized >:)
    
    JPEGDIR=<path>
    
        Set this to the path where you want JPEG files to be decompressed.
        Example: JPEGDIR=Work:Images. The default is RAM:T

    USEMEM=TRUE
    USEMEM=FALSE
    
        If USEMEM=TRUE, the JPEG files will be decompressed to RAM first,
        then saved to disk. This speeds things up but it uses more memory.
        If you are using RAM: as the JPEGDIR, setting USEMEM is a total
        waste! Only use this if you are decompressing to disk. The default
        is OFF.

    QUIET=TRUE
    QUIET=FALSE
    
        Normally, @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} let's you know when it is loaded or unloaded
        via a pop-up requester. If you find this annoying, set QUIET=TRUE.
        The default is FALSE.
    
    ON=TRUE
    ON=FALSE
    
    OFF=TRUE
    OFF=FALSE
    
        These were added for people who want to use @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} from script
        files. These force @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} to a certain state. If you set ON=TRUE,
        @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} will either load (if it isn't already loaded) or it will
        @{i}stay@{ui} loaded if it already is. OFF works the same way. The
        default for both is FALSE.

    To terminate @{b}AutoPEG@{ub}, simply run it again.
    
    See also @{" using script files " link scrip}.
@endnode

@node scrip "Using AutoPEG from Scripts"

    If you only want to use @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} with certain programs, you should
    use AmigaDOS script files.

    Assume I want to use @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} with Work:Gfx/SillyPaint. I could make
    this script:
    
        @{i}cd Work:Gfx
        Sys:Utilities/AutoPEG QUIET=TRUE ON=TRUE
        SillyPaint
        Sys:Utilities/AutoPEG QUIET=TRUE OFF=TRUE@{ui}
    
    This script will go to the Work:Gfx drawer. It will force @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} on
    (you need ON=TRUE because if @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} was already loaded, running it
    again would shut it down - not what we want!). Then, it runs SillyPaint.
    After SillyPaint is done, it shuts down @{b}AutoPEG@{ub}.
    
    Compendez-vous?
@endnode

@node bugs "Problems :("

    Since we are not living in a perfect world, some problems might
    arise:
    
    1. Copying JPEG files while @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} is loaded is a no-no. Don't
       ask me why, but COPY and @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} don't mix.

    2. The AutoPEG.exe file @{i}must@{ui} be located in C:

    3. Some programs open files twice when they read them (ViewTek
       opens them 3 times!). This won't affect the final result, but
       it gets kinda boring waiting for the file to be decompressed
       so many times.

    4. Some programs just won't work with @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} (again, don't ask
       me why!!). In this situation, my advice is: @{b}PUNT!@{ub}.
       (The only one I've found so far is Adpec's Aladdin - ok though
       since Aladdin has built in JPEG!)

    Don't be discouraged! I've tested @{b}AutoPEG@{ub} successfully with:
       DCTV Paint
       Real 3d (the older version)
       ViewTek
       Brilliance
       ImageEngineer (An excellent PD image proc program)

    If you find others that work or don't work, send 'em to me to
    add to the list.

@endnode
